05721nmm a2201309Ia 9780691230474DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912304747 a10.1515/97806912304742doi  a(DE-B1597)653188  a(OCoLC)1381712824  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBF637.F67bC54 2023 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a155.922231 aCherry, Myisha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFailures of Forgiveness :bWhat We Get Wrong and How to Do Better /cMyisha Cherry. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b3 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhilosopher Myisha Cherry teaches us the right ways to deal with wrongdoing in our lives and the worldSages from Cicero to Oprah have told us that forgiveness requires us to let go of negative emotions and that it has a unique power to heal our wounds. In Failures of Forgiveness, Myisha Cherry argues that these beliefs couldn’t be more wrong—and that the ways we think about and use forgiveness, personally and as a society, can often do more harm than good. She presents a new and healthier understanding of forgiveness—one that will give us a better chance to recover from wrongdoing and move toward “radical repair.”Cherry began exploring forgiveness after some relatives of the victims of the mass shooting at Emanuel A.M.E. Church in Charleston, South Carolina, forgave what seemed unforgiveable. She was troubled that many observers appeared to be more inspired by these acts of forgiveness than they were motivated to confront the racial hatred that led to the killings. That is a big mistake, Cherry argues. Forgiveness isn’t magic. We can forgive and still be angry, there can be good reasons not to forgive, and forgiving a wrong without tackling its roots solves nothing. Examining how forgiveness can go wrong in families, between friends, at work, and in the media, politics, and beyond, Cherry addresses forgiveness and race, canceling versus forgiving, self-forgiveness, and more. She takes the burden of forgiveness off those who have been wronged and offers guidance both to those deciding whether and how to forgive and those seeking forgiveness.By showing us how to do forgiveness better, Failures of Forgiveness promises to transform how we deal with wrongdoing in our lives, opening a new path to true healing and reconciliation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aForgivenessxPhilosophy. 0aRestorative justice. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAfricana Philosophy, Feminist Philosophy.  aCanceling.  aConflict.  aEmotions.  aFailures of Forgiveness.  aFamily.  aHow to Do forgiveness Better.  aJesus.  aLove.  aMoral Psychology.  aMyisha Cherry.  aPhilosophy of Race.  aPolarization.  aPolitical Divisions.  aPrinceton University Press.  aReckoning.  aReconciliation.  aRegret.  aRelationships.  aRepair.  aSafe space.  aSocial Philosophy, Political Philosophy.  aThe Case for Rage.  aWhat We Get Wrong about forgiveness.  aabused.  aabusive.  aanger eradicators.  aanger moderators.  aanger.  aapartheid.  aapology.  aattidude.  abehavioral.  abooks about forgiveness.  acherry.  acognitive.  acommunication.  acompassion.  acontempt.  acultural meaning of forgiveness.  aempowerment.  aforgive.  aforgiveness.  agaslighting.  agoodwill extenders.  agrief.  aguilt trip.  ahow to forgive.  aletting go.  amanipulaton.  amartin luther king jr.  amoral operators.  amorality.  anegative feelings.  apolice violence.  arace conflict.  arelease.  arelief.  arelig